<TEXT>
in days past weddings in hamad badrs family 
called for the slaughter of 20 sheep but when a brother got married 
three months ago two were sacrifice enough 
the wedding was a victim of the 20month intefadeh or uprising 
against israeli occupation which has squeezed livelihoods and 
altered lives for palestinians throughout the west bank and gaza 
strip 
repeated strikes by palestinian workers curfews imposed by the 
israeli army and a drop in tourism have slashed incomes 
as the economy has declined the jordanian dinar the key 
currency in the occupied lands has plunged in value by 50 percent 
further ravaging savings and paychecks 
badr whose family has owned a fourtable restaurant in 
jerusalems walled old city for 25 years said his business has been 
devastated 
before if you wanted to get food youd have to wait outside 
for half an hour said badr who now closes for the day at noon to 
comply with the orders of clandestine uprising leaders 
today you see in a half an hour we sold only two cocacolas 
nearly all palestinians insist that the struggle for daily bread 
has not weakened their will to resist israeli occupation but the 
dinars recent plunge coincided with a seeming drop of intensity in 
the uprising and an increase in factional squabbling in palestinian 
ranks 
if you are angry and hungry you have to satisfy your hunger 
first explained tarik said who owns a photo shop near badrs 
restaurant 
but he said that rather than forcing an end to resistance more 
violence is the likely result 
an official of israels military government in the occupied lands 
said economic hardship was beginning to be felt in a widespread way 
for the first time but that it was too early to say it would mean an 
end to the uprising 
samir saleh an economist at the west banks bir zeit university 
said palestinian incomes have fallen and buying power is probably 
half what it was when the uprising began in december 1987 
average incomes per capita declined by 25 percent from a 
preuprising level of 1000 a month 
saleh said the falling value of the dinar has disastrous 
effects the currency has been a major means of payment and 
savings for palestinians since jordan lost the west bank to israel 
in 1967 
here people only believed in god and the dinar said nabil 
feidy a money changer on salah aldin st in east jerusalem 
the dinar was worth 3 early last year but fell to less than 1 
in july before recovering recently to about 150 
hospital workers college teachers islamic preachers and tens of 
thousands of private employees still earn wages in dinars and most 
paychecks have not risen as the dinars purchasing power declined 
sheik hassan ali an islamic preacher who dropped by to visit 
badr said he was forced to move his wife and two children out of 
their apartment and into a single room of his fathers house 
my salary is 160 dinars said ali noting that it used to be 
worth about 480 but now is worth 200 
the impact on people here is devastating said feidy the 
money changer the worst part is that people have their dinars in 
jordanian banks and they cant bring them 
in an effort to stem the flow of orders and money from the 
palestine liberation organization israel sharply curtailed travel 
and financial transfers across the jordan river palestinians can 
now bring in only 200 dinars a person per month 
israel has countered a tax boycott by palestinians with increased 
fees on vehicles 
abu jafaar a teacher who has seen his salary cut in half because 
of the frequent strikes and school closures said fees on his car 
have risen to the equivalent of about 700 a year from 80 
he has opened a small grocery store in his home 
the shop is not a way of living but it helps he said 
