<TEXT>
tim campbell wants to improve third world 
cities by making them smell better 
not only are odors from bad sanitation and bad fuel for cooking 
and heating offensive to the nose theyre unhealthy says campbell 
a senior urban planner for the world bank 
people in karachi pakistans biggest city burn a lot of dung 
and wood in mexico city its wood and charcoal 
that pollutes indoor air in a way that may be related to a range 
of lung diseases tuberculosis and cancer campbell says the 
pollution comes from poor ventilation regardless of the kind of 
fuel 
campbells study environmental dilemmas and the urban poor 
was made public wednesday as part of a more general report called 
environment and the poor development strategies for a common 
agenda 
women and children who spend more time at home are probably 
affected more than men he said 
the adverse effects of household airborne and watercarried 
wastes on child mortality and female life expectancy are of no less 
global proportions than say the destruction of tropical forests 
and in immediate human terms may be the most urgent of all worldwide 
environmental problems campbell wrote 
the bank is the biggest source of aid loans to third world 
countries lending more than 19 billion a year 
dealing with bad smells human waste and indoor air pollution 
will get you a bigger immediate return in human wellbeing than 
many other things we do said john sewell head of the overseas 
development council which published the report 
the council is a private research group financed by foundations 
campbell reported that new kinds of cooking stoves designed for 
third world use have run into trouble because they arent what 
people are accustomed to but he added that they are a good idea 
because a 10 percent improvement of cooking efficiency could save 
millions of tons of wood a year and help solve the health problem 
contain the heat vent the exhausts he advised 
ventilated pit latrines cut down costs by twothirds and standard 
specifications can be reduced to make them cheaper and to use more 
local labor he said 
he called for more research not only on stoves but also on 
toilets that flush when water is poured into them and small 
maneuverable pumps for latrine systems such things may seem second 
class but the people who use them and the donors who provide them 
will learn to appreciate them he said 
shortterm gains in health may come to be valued by the poor as 
much as or more than the loss of status they perceive for having a 
secondclass that is less than standard system for cooking and 
waste disposal he wrote 
