<TEXT>
the oil industry is intensifying its attack on 
a bush administration plan requiring the use of methanol in some 
cars by 1995 to control the growing smog problem in the nations 
most polluted cities 
the american petroleum institute which represents the major oil 
companies has hired consultant thomas austin to speak against 
replacing gasolineburning engines with those capable of running on 
methanol or wood alcohol 
austin a mechanical engineer and former environmental protection 
agency official told reporters wednesday that his research showed 
methanol is no less environmentally harmful than gasoline he also 
contends it is more costly and less safe 
methanol is not an inherently clean fuel he said it is 
just as dirty as gasoline 
the oil industry has voiced strong doubts about methanol since 
bush proposed in june that 500000 cars capable of burning methanol 
be sold by 1995 in cities with the most serious air pollution 
problems and that 1 million be sold each year starting in 1997 
the administration contends that methanolburning cars will help 
reduce the formation of smog because they emit fewer hydrocarbons 
it also says increased use of methanol will reduce the nations 
growing reliance on foreign oil used to make gasoline 
the oil industry which produces about 100 billion gallons of 
gasoline a year has a powerful interest in keeping it the 
predominant transportation fuel 
austin acknowledged that tests show cars running on methanol emit 
fewer poisonous hydrocarbons than those burning gasoline but he 
said the administration has overlooked or discounted research that 
indicates methanolburning engines emit far more formaldehyde a 
chemical that helps form smog 
the major oil companies say they have been researching possible 
uses of methanol as a transportation fuel for years and will 
continue to do so but through their trade association they have 
strongly criticized the bush proposal as too ambitious 
they say more emphasis should be put on researching cleaner 
formulations of gasoline 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

