<TEXT>
lured like other visitors to california 
by the warm climate record numbers of exotic insects are invading 
los angeles county and posing an unprecedented threat to the states 
16 billion a year farm economy 
as of july 1185 potentially harmful pests have appeared in 
california including fruit flies and gypsy moths fire ants 
russian wheat aphids japanese beetles mealy bugs and scales 
we are being literally swamped said rosser w garrison a 
county entomologist who supplied the statistics the variety of 
insects is increasing and the sheer number is increasing 
besides the climate los angeles has become a magnet for imported 
insects because of the ease of international travel more than 37 
million foreigners passed through us customs at los angeles 
international airport last year and at least some presumably 
slipped fresh fruit and vegetables past inspectors officials said 
one of the new pests the ash whitefly already has reached 
epidemic proportions in southern california and is racing for the 
states agricultural heartland the san joaquin valley in central 
california 
the city a hub for commerce with asia and south america boasts 
a burgeoning immigrant population with a taste for fruits and 
vegetables from their native countries 
they have friends and family who are sending them a taste of 
home said robert g atkins a deputy county agricultural 
commissioner 
atkins said that although los angeles countys farm production is 
negligible the county acts as the entry for pests to the rest of 
the state the nations leading agricultural producer 
he noted that californias belated response to a mediterranean 
fruit fly infestation drew widespread publicity nine years ago 
eventually costing the state 100 million to exterminate and farmers 
100 million in losses but similar invasions lately have become 
almost mundane 
i hate to stress that because i dont want people to believe 
that the bug is any less dangerous atkins said 
nevertheless three medfly infestations have occurred in the 
county within the last 12 months each costing roughly 1 million to 
eradicate and each drawing comparatively scant public attention 
the countys budget for plant quarantine last year was more than 
784000 an almost 54 percent increase over fiscal year 197778 
officials said 
treatment methods vary for different types of fruit flies but 
early detection is a fundamental strategy made possible by checking 
more than 160000 baited traps set throughout the state 
its almost like battling forest fires garrison said its 
a lot easier to put it out as soon as it gets started 
discoveries of less notorious pests are charted each month by 
garrison whose microscopic scrutiny detected five new types of 
insects in the county last year and three so far this year 
although agriculture officials have established methods of 
dealing with fruit fly infestations other kinds of insects can be 
neither readily identified nor exterminated 
