<TEXT>
a radiocontrolled insulin pump implanted in 
diabetics abdomens can free them from injections and may more 
closely mimic the way nature provides the essential hormone 
according to a study published today 
the pump can be programmed to vary the rate at which it releases 
insulin researchers hope this approach will help diabetics get 
better control of their blood sugar levels and avoid the disabling 
complications of their disease such as blindness and kidney failure 
its a significant advance said dr christopher d saudek of 
johns hopkins university where the pump was developed this is 
in my view the first successful longterm experience with 
variablerate implanted insulin pumps 
other implanted pumps tested in recent years have been hindered 
by problems such as clogged lines 
the new pump was tested on 18 diabetics and doctors said it 
generally worked well although four pumps became blocked when 
tissue grew over the catheter that releases the insulin one 
malfunctioned because of a faulty microchip 
doctors can program the pumps to vary the rate at which they 
release insulin throughout the day patients use a handheld radio 
transmitter to command the pumps to give out an extra burst of 
insulin after meals 
while blood sugar control with the pumps was good the doctors 
said that the best solution eventually may be a pump that senses the 
bodys blood sugar levels and releases insulin as its needed 
an estimated 500000 diabetic americans require frequent insulin 
injections because their bodies fail to make enough of the hormone 
that breaks down sugar 
the new pumps manufactured by minimed technologies of sylmar 
calif were tested by saudek and other doctors at johns hopkins and 
the university of california irvine they described the results in 
a report in the new england journal of medicine 
patients used the pump called a programmable implantable 
medication system or pims for all their insulin needs for periods 
ranging from four months to two years except for two who withdrew 
from the experiment because of blocked catheters the doctors said 
that patients have been uniformly happy with their pumps 
the diskshaped pumps implanted in patients abdomens are 3 
inches in diameter and weigh 7 ounces they hold about 2 teaspoons 
of insulin a twomonth supply and can be refilled with a syringe 
the devices have computer memories that will record an hourly 
history of all insulin released during three weeks 
researchers plan soon to test a slightly modified version of the 
pump on more patients 
the expectation is that if these next trials go well we would 
then apply to have the pump generally available to the diabetic 
population saudek said 
the mechanism was based on the design of a device on the viking 
space probe that delivered culture medium to martian soil to see if 
anything would grow in it 
</TEXT>
