the food and drug administration has extended 
for two months its deadline for deciding whether to ban red dye no 
3 as a cancercausing food additive 
the agency in announcing the extension wednesday said it has 
been evaluating research data submitted by the certified color 
manufacturers association on the coloring that gives maraschino 
cherries their bright glow 
the fda had been prepared to act by the earlier deadline which 
was wednesday when the house in july passed legislation calling for 
further study of the dye the senate has not yet acted on the 
legislation 
since 1960 when congress called for a ban on foods that cause 
cancer in laboratory animals red dye no 3 and other additives have 
been on a provisional list that allowed them to stay on the market 
for an additional two years pending further study 
since then the fda has granted dozens of extensions of the 
provisional listing 
the manufacturers association says the dye is not a primary cause 
of cancer and causes tumors only when used in doses higher than 
would ever be consumed through its use as a food coloring 
