<TEXT>
when overweight youngsters switch from highsalt to 
lowsalt diets their blood pressures fall dramatically but the 
change in food has no effect on normalsize youngsters a study 
published today shows 
the work suggests that fat youngsters are more susceptible to the 
damaging effects of a highsalt diet this helps explain why 
overweight people are especially prone to get high blood pressure 
doctors have long known that people who lose weight also lower 
their blood pressure the latest work shows that mild sodium 
restriction also results in a significant drop in blood pressure 
even when people remain overweight 
in this study we found that the blood pressure of obese 
adolescents is sensitive to dietary sodium intake whereas the blood 
pressure of nonobese adolescents is not the researchers wrote 
they theorized that overweight people get high blood pressure 
because their bodies are less efficient at getting rid of salt 
the study was directed by dr albert p rocchini of the 
university of michigan medical center in ann arbor and published in 
the new england journal of medicine 
the researchers studied 60 obese and 18 normal youngsters who 
ranged from age 10 to 16 they spent two weeks on a highsalt diet 
and two weeks on a lowsalt diet 
at the start of the study the overweight youngsters blood 
pressures were 19 points higher than the normal childrens after 
the lowsalt regimen the obese youngsters fell 12 points while 
the normal childrens rose one 
thirtysix of the overweight children went on weightloss diets 
and dropped an average of 17 pounds at the lower weights their 
blood pressures were no longer sensitive to salt 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

