<TEXT>
vice premier yao yilin said thursday the 
government will take even tougher retrenchment measures in the next 
three years to reduce inflation and restore market order 
finance minister wang bingqian meanwhile predicted chinas 
money shortage wil grow more acute next year when more foreign loans 
start coming due 
the two officials delivered their sober assessments of chinas 
economic situation to the standing committee of the national 
peoples congress the legislature which began meeting tuesday 
yao said consumer demand continued to grow and many measures 
intended to cut investment didnt work as expected the official 
xinhua news agency reported workers income is still growing faster 
than their productivity he said and agricultural growth still lags 
far behind that of industry 
the government will take tougher measures in the comming three 
years to accomplish the ongoing economic retrenchment xinhua said 
yao reported it gave no specifics of what measures would be taken 
however the official china daily reported earlier thursday the 
government would crack down on illegal trading in key raw materials 
such as coal and steel eliminate middlemen in the distribution 
chain discipline illegal raw material dealers and begin an 
investigation of private businesses to ensure they pay taxes 
it quoted xie mingan of the ministry of materials and equipment 
as saying efforts would be made to control steel and coal prices and 
the trend of privatizing distribution of more and more materials 
would be halted 
the government said monday that any local officials who fail to 
cut investment will be punished 
the government has been trying since september 1988 to reassert 
many controls over the economy that were weakened or abolished over 
a decade of reform inflation that peaked at about 36 percent it 
now is running at a 25 percent annual rate combined with shortages 
of key materials hoarding black marketeering and panic runs on 
banks triggered the pullback 
measures already taken include orders to cut capital 
construction new restrictions on borrowing and government control 
of the prices and distribution of some goods 
yao told the legislature that the policies had succeeded in 
cutting industrial growth production in the first seven months of 
the year was up just 106 percent from the same period last year 
which had been up 17 percent from the year before that 
he said bank savings were up wang said state revenue exceeded 
expenditures over the seven months although revenue grew more 
slowly than spending 
but both officials spoke gloomily of the future xinhua headlined 
wangs report financial situation dire and quoted yao as 
saying china faces great economic difficulty 
wang noted that government subsidies have ballooned in recent 
years as it has bailed out inefficient stateowned companies and 
tried to give farmers a better price for their grain while keeping 
groceries cheap for urban residents 
borrowing also has accelerated chinas foreign debt zero in 
1978 totaled 40 billion at the end of 1988 including 10 billion 
in shortterm loans 
the government also has borrowed 93 billion from its own 
citizens over the past decade by issuing treasury bonds many 
chinese workers are required to buy the bonds with the price 
automatically deducted from their pay 
wang blamed the problems on ousted party general secretary zhao 
ziyangs errors in financial decisions including violating what 
he called the socialist financial principle of balancing the 
budget zhao who lost his post in a power struggle in june over 
handling of the spring democracy protests had advocated rapid 
growth 
chinese officials have issued repeated assurances recently that 
the country will be able to repay its debt 
</TEXT>
