<TEXT>
the main subgroup of the un human rights 
commission urged thursday that the commission take up the situation 
in china 
john pace a un human rights spokesman said it was the first 
time conditions in one of the five permanent security council 
members were referred to the human rights commission the other 
permanent members are the united sates soviet union britain and 
france 
a resolution adopted 159 in a secret ballot by the 
subcommission on prevention of discrimination and the protection of 
minorities expressed concern about recent events in china and 
their consequences in the field of human rights 
it appealed to chinese authorities for clemency in dealing for 
those imprisoned after the army brutally suppressed prodemocracy 
demonstrations in june 
the resolution asked the un secretarygeneral to transmit to 
the commission on human rights further information provided by the 
government of china and other reliable sources 
china rejected the resolution as interference in its internal 
affairs 
asbjorn eide a norwegian member of the subcommission described 
the resolution as very conciliatory 
he said the main purpose was to focus attention on china in the 
human rights commission which includes delegates from 43 
governments and will hold its next meeting in february it is the 
highest un human rights body and can appoint special investigators 
a chinese statement thursday said this resolution contradicts 
the purpose of the un charter and runs counter to the norms of 
governing international relations the chinese government rejects 
this resolution it is null and void and has no binding force on 
china whatsoever 
the resolution was sponsored by panel members from the united 
states britain france the netherlands norway japan mexico and 
the philippines 
western delegates sought the secret ballot as a means of guarding 
the independence of the 26member panel 
on wednesday amnesty international said at least 1000 people 
were killed in beijings tiananmen square when soldiers moved 
against the unarmed demonstrators june 34 it accused the chinese 
government of secret executions and mass arrests 
china denied the charges at a weekly briefing thursday in 
beijing foreign ministry spokesman li zhaoxing said amnesty claims 
of a wave of repression after the crackdown are entirely 
ungrounded and unreasonable 
an extremely small number of people used terrorist means and 
took violent actions in an attempt to overthrow the legitimate 
government he said that the chinese government according to 
law arrested those criminals and sentenced them to imprisonment is 
entirely legitimate and justified 
no country or organization has the right to interfere in an 
issue that is purely another countrys internal affair 
