<TEXT>
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter said 
thursday the farmers home administration has turned from being a 
lender into a grant agency and that he is determined to put it 
on a more businesslike footing 
weve just got to reform that program take it out of the 
status of what its really become a grant agency and move it 
back to being a credit institution once again yeutter said 
the fmha has its roots in the great depression of the 1930s and 
is often called the governments farm lender of last resort to be 
eligible for loans farmers must be unable to get regular loans from 
banks or other commercial institutions 
yeutter said the agriculture department agency has made 
billions of dollars of questionable loans over the last decade or 
so many of which are in default today 
but he noted that attempts have been made to change fmha and to 
toughen its lending practices only to be thwarted by legal action 
filed by farmers or their advocates or by congress 
if we have to change legislation in this area in order to do a 
more effective and skillful job of managing fmha well make 
legislative proposals to have that happen yeutter told a 
television news conference if we can do it administratively 
well do it that way 
for years the fmha has been embroiled in controversial attempts 
to collect longoverdue farm loans new procedures to help protect 
the interests of farmers and to enable the agency to proceed with 
its collections were included by congress in the agricultural credit 
act of 1987 
the latest move involves fmha sending out a new batch of 
collection notices to borrowers who failed to make their scheduled 
payments by the first of this year 
agency spokesman marlyn aycock said the fmhas county offices 
were told to mail out the collection notices by aug 25 so that 
delinquent borrowers could have them by sept 1 
the county offices were sent lists of delinquents totaling 13217 
borrowers as of aug 1 and were instructed to delete names of those 
who had settled their accounts since then 
aycock said those deletions possibly could reduce the list to 
between 11000 and 12000 names by the time they were mailed out 
last week 
but we wont get an actual count until farther down the road 
he said 
the list of delinquencies has shrunk dramatically since jan 1 
when it was more than 30000 borrowers he said by july 3 it was 
down to 15704 names and the aug 1 count dropped to 13217 the 
basic list sent to county offices 
borrowers will have 45 days from receipt of the notices to return 
forms to fmha describing how they want to settle their overdue 
accounts the 1987 law requires the agency to tell farmers they have 
certain options including reamortization or rescheduling payment 
deferral reduced interest rates and in some cases debt 
forgiveness 
if farmers do not respond or if a borrower is in such poor 
financial shape that no alternative can be worked out forced sale 
or foreclosure proceedings could begin 
aycock said the latest notices are in addition to more than 
66000 sent out last fall to delinquent borrowers many of whom had 
not made payments for three years or more 
the total owed fmha by all delinquent borrowers is around 87 
billion although there is no breakdown showing how much the 1989 
notices involve he said 
