several important manuscripts by french philosopher 
jeanpaul sartre and his companion writer simone de beauvoir have 
been accepted as payment of estate taxes from de beauvoirs heirs 
officials announced thursday 
the texts include the manuscripts of sartres work flaubert 
the idiot of the family the critique of dialectical reason 
and 399 letters sartre wrote to de beavoir between 1926 and 1963 
some of which have never been published 
most exciting is the discovery of 255 letters from de beauvoir to 
sartre which literary historians did not know existed 
the two intellectuals met while university students and 
corresponded regularly during a relationship which ended with 
sartres death in 1980 
de beavoir best known for her bestselling and influential 
feminist essay the second sex died in 1986 
frances budget minister michel charasse made the announcement 
all the texts taken as payment of estate taxes become the property 
of the government and part of the french national collections 
the texts also include nine of ms de beauvoirs her private 
diaries her unpublished misunderstanding in moscow 
monologue and old age 
among works by sartre a leading proponent of existentialism 
are the novel nausea the plays no exit and the flies 
and the treatise being and nothingness 
