a sevenpronged 191 million research program 
to understand how mans activities and pollution are changing the 
planet was laid out thursday by a group of federal agencies 
the goal is to monitor understand and ultimately predict 
global change said robert post of the office of science and 
technology policy 
global change is a large complex scientific problem and it 
still is not largely understood said dallas peck director of the 
u s geological survey and chairman of the federal committee on 
earth science which is coordinating the research effort 
there is a shared common purpose to understand global change 
were in the planning stages added dixon butler of the national 
aeronautics and space administration 
the effort announced thursday covers the coming fiscal year 
beginning oct 1 peck described it as largely a planning period to 
be used setting up research programs likely to last a decade or more 
the atmosphere and the role of clouds received top priority in in 
the program michael hall of the national oceanic and atmospheric 
administration said clouds are a major factor in the feared rise in 
global temperatures and their effect is not well understood 
the widely discussed threat of global warming however is only 
part of the overall research effort the studies also will look at 
threats to the earths protective ozone layer possible changes in 
the oceans and atmosphere air pollution acid rain and other 
processes 
reports of warmer temperatures have drawn the most attention 
recently some scientists are concerned that carbon dioxide and 
other gases added to the atmosphere by human activities are causing 
the higher temperatures and tha eventually they might lead to 
disruptive climate changes 
other scientists dispute the socalled greenhouse effect and 
evidence is lacking on both sides that is an area the researchers 
hope to tackle early 
funds totaling 1915 million for fiscal 1990 are included in the 
budgets of various departments to get the program under way said 
bob corell of the national science foundation in january the 
committee will put together requests for funds for 1991 and future 
years he said 
the seven major areas of research set forth thursday are 
climate and hydrologic systems the role of clouds is the first 
item on the agenda followed by research in ocean circulation and 
interaction of the air land and water 
biogeochemical dynamics the relationship between living 
organisms and the water and atmosphere for example trees take 
carbon dioxide out of the air and replace it with oxygen cutting 
down trees reduces that activity 
ecological systems and dynamics how people plants and animals 
would react to climate change and how those reactions might in turn 
affect other processes 
earth system history what has happened to the land air and 
water when climate has changed in the past 
human interactions population growth and development energy 
and land use and industrial production and how those activities 
affect the earth 
solid earth research coastal erosion volcanoes and their 
effect on climate permafrost the seafloor and other areas 
solar influences monitoring incoming radiation from the sun 
the amount reflected back into space and how this energy affects the 
earth and its climate 
in addition to the geological survey nasa and noaa other 
agencies in the program are the state department environmental 
protection agency department of transportation department of 
agriculture council on environmental quality and the department of 
defense 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

