<DOCNO> AP890831-0214 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when james lee left prison five years ago no 
one believed he was a changed man after all lee began smoking 
marijuana at age 13 and graduated to snorting cocaine and heroin at 
14 feeding an appetite for drugs that for two decades dictated a 
life of crime 
i knew the ins and outs of drugs he says explaining that as 
a youngster he had seen the debilitating effects of illicit drug 
use but it was the slick thing to do i wanted to belong to do 
what everybody else was doing at the time 
so at 13 he began an involvement with drugs that would last 
almost 20 years 
now a successful businessman who spends his free time speaking at 
churches and counseling inmates at the lorton correctional 
facilities in suburban virginia lee says he is committed to help 
others change the deadend course of their lives 
my whole life had been filled with drugs and hustling said 
the 45yearold lee whose closely cropped hair now has an even mix 
of gray 
occasional use of marijuana then cocaine and heroin became an 
obsession by age 15 and thats when the crimes increased because 
i had to get drugs every day he said 
at first money for the drugs came from petty thefts and what he 
described as yoke robberies strongarm robberies or holdups 
without weapons 
despite all of this lee continued to attend school and to 
conceal his drug habit and crimes from his mother a christian who 
demanded church attendance most of the expensive clothes and 
jewelry he bought with his illgotten money were stored at friends 
houses 
lees first car at age 16 a 1964 mustang that then held the 
same prestige as todays bmw was parked around corners and in 
friends garages and driveways 
robbery was the thing in the 60s we went from bank robbery to 
robbing private businesses said lee whose first adult arrest 
came in the summer of 1966 when he joined some friends who hijacked 
a truck full of merchandise the charges were later dropped 
his profession as a thief ended in april 1968 when lee was 
arrested for felony murder after an accomplice shot a clerk during a 
postal robbery while waiting 18 months in jail to go to trial he 
met two men from new york who convinced him that selling drugs would 
reap greater profits faster 
so when charges again were dropped lee headed for new york 
where his friends introduced me to a new hustle selling drugs 
the money came so fast there was no comparison with money 
from the robberies said lee thats part of the problem today 
the money is fast there is no money in the world faster than drug 
money 
lees success was meteoric i was able to acquire a grocery 
store a new home an apartment building new cars fine clothes 
jewelry and traveled around the world i met people that put me in a 
position to get more and better drugs 
but as his business skyrocketed so did his craving for drugs 
i went from snorting drugs to shooting drugs because i had a raw 
habit he said when you become your best customer you become 
unreliable as far as the supplier is concerned as far as paying 
money back 
lees drug suppliers entrusted him with smaller and smaller 
amounts of drugs dropping from 10 kilograms down to five kilos and 
then three he also had frequent skirmishes with the law and was 
convicted four times on drug charges 
when you know people getting drugs or going to jail wasnt a 
problem to me because my life pattern never had to change said 
lee explaining that drugs were just as plentiful in jail as on 
the streets if not more plentiful 
lee who married at age 17 said his son brought him drugs in 
prison concealing them in tennis balls or using other ingenious 
smuggling techniques 
my last arrest had me facing 60 years in jail lee said but 
he was sentenced to only 20 monthstofive years at lorton 
it was during his last incarceration that lee met several 
christian inmates who persuaded him to change his life after his 
release he was still viewed skeptically by his family especially 
his wife who had left him three years into the marriage 
people didnt want to believe it theyve heard before id 
changed and then id come out and do the same thing he said 
but the longer i stayed out the more they had to reevaluate 
whether or not i was serious 
lees family began to respect his commitment then in april 1988 
his 24yearold son a dealer himself was killed on the street 
shot nine times lee said he successfully suppressed his urge to 
retaliate against his sons murderers 
today lee is production manager of a print shop in reston va 
making 40000 a year that he can spend without worrying about the 
police kicking my door in 
after a 20year separation lee and his wife reunited last 
november and live in suburban maryland 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

