<TEXT>
terry robson says more than one person has 
compared his business to the ghostbusters of movie fame he has a 
team armed with chemicals that goes into offices to fight 
invisible enemies 
the enemies in this case are the indoor pollutants that 
environmental officials say are threatening workers health 
increased awareness of indoor pollution which some say is as 
dangerous as the toxins floating around outdoors is creating plenty 
of work for companies such as robsons britetech international inc 
five or seven years ago it was hard to go in and convince 
someone they had indoor pollution said robson president and 
founder of britetech of norcross which franchises its services 
theyd look around and say i dont see it 
an environmental protection agency survey conducted last year 
found that 1200 companies were providing indoor environmental 
cleaning or analysis work most of it for radon or asbestos 
bob axelrad director of the indoor air division of the epas 
office of air and radiation in washington dc said many of these 
companies are expanding into the field of indoor air pollution 
though the survey did not give a precise figure 
our sense is it is a growing business axelrad said a lot 
of those doing industrial hygiene work are finding pretty good 
demand for their services he said 
we definitely think this is an emerging issue axelrad said 
of indoor pollution 
an epa report released last spring said pesticides radon 
asbestos tobacco smoke bacteria and mold inhaled in poorly 
ventilated offices may threaten the health of americans as much as 
outdoor pollution 
the epa report attributed more than 1 billion in medical costs 
from cancer and heart disease to eight indoor pollutants 
the combination of indoor pollutants has earned the name sick 
building syndrome americans spend most of their time indoors and 
robson said that as more people become aware of the syndrome they 
want something done about it 
people often are surprised by the pollution found in an office or 
other indoor environment robson said the toxins in cigarette 
smoke for example stick to walls and ceilings and stay there for 
years he said 
there are 350 types of gases and pollutants in tobacco smoke 
he said if the building was contaminated before the residue is 
still there 
charles almond staff engineer at north carolina baptist hospital 
in winstonsalem nc a customer of a britetech franchisee said 
hospitals are extremely concerned with indoor pollution but he said 
that only in recent years has the means for fighting the toxins 
grown more sophisticated 
we were very much concerned with odors we cant have any 
because of our criticalcare areas almond said we used to have 
a can of lysol and thats what we used 
almond said the availability of indoor pollutioncontrol 
companies is contributing to cleaner hospitals 
with the growth of an industry that deals with something that 
often cannot be seen however comes inevitable fraud officials 
warn 
martha casey an epa spokesman in washington said the agency 
conducts training programs for both pollution testers and 
mitigators and makes lists of participants available to its 
regional offices in an effort to minimize fraud 
we know there are some con artists out there who come in with 
the mayonnaise jar scoop up some air and then tell them customers 
theyll analyze it and get back to them ms casey said 
britetech uses a variety of measuring tools and also talks to 
building occupants to determine the level of pollution the company 
also suggests remedies and has about 20 formulas all nontoxic and 
biodegradable robson said for cleaning indoor areas 
robson said the cleaning process involves spraying a chemical 
mist onto surfaces which dissolves the toxins there is no 
scrubbing he said 
the cleaning materials also are sprayed into ventilation systems 
though in extreme cases installation of a new air conditioning 
system may be recommended 
though the cost of britetech service varies according to the type 
of surface and degree of pollution robson said franchises generally 
charge 25 cents to 50 cents per square foot 
britetech is a relatively new player in the indoor pollution 
field having started in january robson said he believes britetech 
is the first franchisor in the industry 
the company has 12 franchises operating in nine states 
franchisees must put up a fee of 15000 to 25000 plus 10000 
working capital the norcross headquarters provides training 
materials and a fulltime staff including a chemist 
robson said his companys revenues so far are about 3 million a 
year and he is hoping for 45 units and revenues of 20 million by 
the middle of next year 
