<TEXT>
a group of japanese economists said thursday the 
united states could expect only greater frictions with its trading 
partners if it adopted an advisory committees calls for a more 
resultoriented approach to lowering the us trade deficit 
the economists also said japan must reexamine such business 
practices as the tendency of japanese doing business mainly with 
each other manufacturers dominance in pricesetting and 
discriminatory treatment against imported products 
but while these practices may be frustrating to american 
exporters they have little to do with the large trade imbalances of 
the united states or japan said masaru yoshitomi directorgeneral 
of the economic research institute and a leading member of the 
japanus business council 
the council presented a counterproposal thursday to 
recommendations in february by us trade representative carla 
hills advisory committee for trade policy and negotiation 
the us panel headed by james robinson chairman of american 
express co recommended that the us trade representative take a 
more resultoriented approach to the us deficit with japan this 
would mean judging japanese actions by how much they reduce the 
deficit 
yoshitomis group recommends handling trade imbalance issues 
separately from trade policy issues saying that lowering barriers 
is a separate issue from achieving a balance between imports and 
exports 
it argues that it is totally wrong to see a large deficit as 
reflecting a countrys free trade practices and a large surplus as 
reflecting trade restrictions 
fundamental confusion is often seen in many journalistic 
articles it says 
referring to growing protectionist sentiment in the united states 
against japanese trade practices the report says the united states 
should not be frustrated by the lack of progress in reducing trade 
deficits and should not let politicians use the sentiment 
politically 
the report also attacks the united states use against japan of 
new trade legislation providing for retaliation if the two sides 
cannot negotiate a solution to japanese trade practices the united 
states deems unfair 
the global free trade system would completely break down if 
every country adopted the same policies based on unilateral 
judgments of unfair trade practices of trading partners in specific 
products especially when no country always acts fairly including 
the united states it says 
yoshitomi stressed that americans must change in order to reduce 
their trade deficit rather than simply demanding that its trade 
partners change 
us technological hegemony was established through essentially 
a mass production system since early this century he said 
but the situation may have changed in favor of japan so that 
many aspects of the american system must adapt he said 
