volkswagen of america has moved its northeast 
distribution center from the port of albany to rhode island the 
second major shipper the albany port has lost in two months 
officials said 
volkswagen said wednesday it was transferring its shipping center 
to the port of davisville in rhode island effective immediately 
the west german automaker had shipped more than 100000 cars up the 
hudson river to albany in the last three years 
the pullout will mean work reductions for up to 175 longshoremen 
while about a dozen jobs will be lost in related businesses 
officials said 
volkswagen shipped about 20500 cars to albany last year 
accounting for 135000 in revenues about 9 percent of the ports 
receipts 
the move comes after united brands co which shipped bananas 
from central america to albany for 17 years moved its shipments to 
wilmington del this summer united brands and volkswagen had been 
the ports biggest clients accounting for 80 percent of 
longshoremens work union officials said 
volkswagen was the last major steady client for us said 
wallace turnwall port manager for international terminal operators 
which manages the port 
volkswagen decided to leave albany after 11 years despite 
incentives offered by the port and union leaders the albany times 
union reported those incentives included freezing dock fees in 
1990 the newspaper reported 
its simply more economical to import through rhode island than 
to albany volkswagen spokesman patrick fitzgerald told the 
newspaper 
