<TEXT>
ever since the coffee beans muddy broth was 
first served 1000 years ago its survived religious persecution 
official banishment and suspected links to maladies ranging from 
heart attacks to male impotence 
its been written about used for inspiration and put to music 
johann sebastian bach composed coffee cantata which parodied 
those who sought to suppress the brew french philosopher voltaire 
reportedly drank 50 cups a day 
coffee as a drink first appeared in the year 900 in a part of 
arabia that is now yemen it became so popular in the middle east 
that moslem priests complained the drink emptied the mosques 
coffees rapid spread to europe led devout catholics to denounce it 
as an infidels brew 
frederick the great of prussia once banned coffee because he 
thought it threatened consumption of beer the national drink 
a study of coffee by findsvp a new york research concern said 
coffees success in 16th century europe led women to agitate for a 
prohibition claiming the drink inhibited the virility of their 
mates 
in more modern times medical studies have concluded the 
stimulant caffeine in coffee may contribute to higher cholesterol 
levels and heart disease 
health concerns about coffee is one reason its popularity among 
americans is diminishing according to recent studies which show a 
longterm decline in us consumption 
while three out of four americans regularly downed at least a cup 
a day in 1962 only half of the population reported drinking coffee 
last year a study by the international coffee organization shows 
in 1988 the average number of cups of coffee consumed per person 
per day was 167 cups down from 176 cups in 1987 and 46 percent 
below 1962 when per capita consumption was 312 cups the ico study 
found 
even hard core drinkers drink less 334 cups per day in 1988 
compared with 417 cups in 1962 
that doesnt mean coffee drinking is doomed in the united states 
which remains the largest market for coffee although americans 
constitute only 5 percent of the world population they still drink 
a third of the planets coffee about 360 million cups a day a 
report by the consumers union shows 
americans have also become more selective about their brew 
consumption of instant coffee has dipped appreciably in the last 
three decades though the number of people drinking decaffeinated 
coffee last year was four times that of 1962 the amount consumed 
declined from 175 percent in 1987 to 158 percent in 1988 the ico 
study found 
the most noticeable change has been in the habits of those 2029 
years of age whose per capita consumption fell from about 3 cups a 
day in 1962 to less than one cup in 1988 people older than 30 who 
consumed more than 4 cups in 1962 now drink about two cups a day 
analysts also attribute the decline in coffee drinking to the 
rise in popularity of soft drinks which has increased 
proportionally since 1985 soft drinks have overtaken coffee as the 
most consumed beverage 
but consumer concern about natural healthy foods also has led to 
a rise in the popularity of gourmet coffees despite the decline in 
overall coffee consumption sales of gourmet blends have grown about 
25 percent a year since 1975 says the findsvp study 
specialty whole bean and gourmet coffee now constitutes 8 percent 
of the total coffee market says robert dechillo spokesman for the 
national coffee association dechillo defines gourmet coffee as high 
quality flavored or unflavored coffee 
the trend to increased supermarket distribution is the most 
significant development in the industry and in helping popularize 
gourmet coffee it has also grown in restaurants 
with the two biggest us roasters procter amp gamble co and 
general foods corp getting into the act and expanding their 
marketing of gourmet coffees at supermarkets sales of gourmet 
coffee which totaled about 600 million in 1988 are forecast to 
double in another decade the findsvp study says 
of the gourmet segment flavored coffees are the fastest growing 
segment and the most controversial many purists shun flavored 
coffees because they consider them adulterated 
but it is this segment that has captured younger consumers who 
have grown up on soft drinks and sweeteroriented taste buds the 
findsvp study concludes 
the research firm found that vanilla nut irish cream and 
chocolate are consumers favorite flavors other favorites include 
cinnamon chocolate raspberry and coconut 
</TEXT>
