<TEXT>
japanese banks goliaths of international finance 
are growing even bigger leaving their us counterparts in the dust 
as they keep an eye on deregulation 
the 10 largest banks in the world in terms of assets are all 
japanese led by daichi kangyo bank which has assets of 377 
billion thats more than citicorp and chase manhattan bank corp 
the two biggest us banks combined 
on tuesday mitsui bank and taiyo kobe bank said they would merge 
in april forming the worlds secondlargest bank with assets of 
348 billion 
in california four of the top 10 banks are japaneseowned 
deregulation starting in 1991 will allow them to expand across the 
united states backed by the strength of their huge parent companies 
a look at the unwieldy names of japanese banks shows how they got 
so big the mitsui taiyo kobe bank will combine the oldest bank in 
japan with the results of a 1973 merger of taiyo bank and kobe bank 
daichi kangyo bank is the result of a 1971 merger of its namesakes 
and had mitsui achieved its original threeway merger ambitions 
the economic newspaper nihon keizai shimbun says there would have 
been a mitsui taiyo kobe daiwa bank 
mergers of this scale are virtually unthinkable in the united 
states where antitrust regulations prevent the creation of firms 
judged large enough to restrict competition they are also rare in 
europe 
in japan senior ministry of finance officials praised the 
mitsuitaiyo kobe deal as good business strategy the national 
bankers association also welcomed the merger 
although mitsui and taiyo kobe were ranked seventh and eighth 
largest banks in japan each significantly larger than any us 
bank neither bank was really big enough to fulfill its ambitions 
on its own said simon smithson an analyst at kleinwort benson 
securities 
japans fair trade commission said it will look into the merger 
to see if it violates antitrust laws but the usually meek agency 
is not expected to block the deal 
next week us officials are expected to cite what they see as 
japans lax enforcement of antitrust laws in talks on structural 
impediments to correcting japans big surplus in trade with the 
united states 
there have been fears that japanese banks with the enormous cash 
reserves pooled by thrifty japanese savers will dominate 
international markets just as japanese car and electronics 
manufacturers have 
in banking largely through cheap pricing and highvolume 
business japanese banks already have made major inroads into us 
lending and in eurobond issues because of their strong domestic 
market where analysts estimate they make 90 percent of their 
profits they can afford to take slim margins on their overseas 
business 
but sheer size doesnt necessarilymean profitability 
daichi kangyo is ranked first in the world in terms of assets 
but only 77th in terms of return on equity notes j brian 
waterhouse an analyst at the securities house james capel 
some analysts say japans banking is where its manufacturing was 
20 years ago selling simple products cheap 
but foreign analysts say japanese banks are rapidly moving into 
more sophisticated products starting to invent as well as copy and 
that combined with firstclass skills their size will be an 
enormous advantage 
there could be implications for the united states if americans 
found themselves constrained by their own laws from reaching world 
size said an american banker speaking on condition of anonymity 
</TEXT>
