<DOCNO> AP890831-0281 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a federal appeals court on thursday upheld a lower 
courts decision to throw out controversial firstinthenation 
state regulations that would have made it easier for stock traders 
to sue brokers in financial disputes 
the 1st us circuit court of appeals backed up us district 
judge douglas p woodlocks december 1988 ruling throwing out 
massachusetts regulations that prevent stockbrokers from requiring 
customers to seek arbitration in stock disputes 
a coalition of brokers brought the case in september 1988 after 
massachusetts secretary of state michael connolly imposed the 
regulations inspired by the 1987 stock market crash 
the regulations would have required brokers to fully disclose the 
terms of their arbitration agreements and give customers the option 
of maintaining their right to sue in court 
we can find no evidence of a clear congressional command to 
override the unambiguous proarbitration mandate of the federal 
arbitration act in the securities field the court opinion said 
other states interested in instituting requirements similar to 
the massachusetts regulations were watching the case closely 
typically the arbitration agreements state that in the event of 
a dispute the customer and the broker would go into arbitration 
before a mutually acceptable party such as the new york stock 
exchange rather than take the case to court 
among those challenging the regulations were the securities 
industry association and 10 brokerage firms including dean witter 
reynolds inc fidelity brokerage services inc and shearson lehman 
hutton inc 
thousands of investors filed complaints alleging their urgent 
stock transactions were misplaced or mishandled during the stock 
market crash of october 1987 and many have said they prefer lawsuits 
to arbitration 
theres been a certain amount of suspicion that investors dont 
get as good a result in arbitration as in court said attorney 
gerald rath who represents the plaintiffs in the case but as far 
as im concerned thats unfounded 
telephone calls placed to connollys office for comment thursday 
evening were not answered 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

